│ The user wants me to fix a miscompilation in LLVM's GVN pass.                                                                                                                            │
│ The issue is that GVN incorrectly considers two `llvm.ctpop` calls as equivalent, even though they have different `!range` metadata. This leads to replacing a valid value with          │
│ `poison`.                                                                                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The reproducer shows:                                                                                                                                                                    │
│ - `%ctpop1 = tail call range(i32 1, 32) i32 @llvm.ctpop.i32(i32 %x)`                                                                                                                     │
│ - `%ctpop2 = tail call range(i32 0, 33) i32 @llvm.ctpop.i32(i32 %x)`                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ GVN replaces `%ctpop2` with `%ctpop1`. When `%x` is 0, `ctpop(%x)` is 0.                                                                                                                 │
│ - For `%ctpop1`, 0 is outside the range `[1, 32)`, so the value becomes `poison`.                                                                                                        │
│ - For `%ctpop2`, 0 is inside the range `[0, 33)`, so the value is `0`.                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ This miscompilation happens because GVN's instruction comparison logic does not account for the `!range` metadata.                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The relevant code is likely in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/GVN.cpp`. I need to find where GVN compares instructions for equivalence. A good candidate is a function that checks if two   │
│ instructions are identical or congruent.                                                                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ Looking at the GVN code, `areInstsCongruent` seems to be the key function. It compares two instructions to see if they can be considered equivalent for value numbering. This function   │
│ should be modified to compare `!range` metadata.                                                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The `areInstsCongruent` function takes two `Instruction*` arguments. I can get the metadata using `I1->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range)` and `I2->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range)`. │
│ If the metadata pointers are different, the instructions should not be considered congruent. A simple pointer comparison should be sufficient, as identical ranges will likely be        │
│ represented by the same metadata node.                                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ I will add the following check at the beginning of `areInstsCongruent` in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/GVN.cpp`:                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```cpp                                                                                                                                                                                   │
│ if (I1->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range) !=                                                                                                                                            │
│     I2->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range))                                                                                                                                              │
│   return false;                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ This will ensure that if two instructions have different `!range` metadata, they are not treated as congruent by GVN, thus preventing the miscompilation.                                │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ Now, I will apply this change using `sed`.                                                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ sed -i '/bool GVN::areInstsCongruent(const Instruction \*I1, const Instruction \*I2) const {/a \                                                                                         │
│   if (I1->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range) != \                                                                                                                                        │
│       I2->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_range)) \                                                                                                                                          │
│     return false;' llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/GVN.cpp                                                                                                                                    │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
